PARSEC is the science fiction game for the 21st century, designed for adventures in the 23rd. You are the children of Sol, hardened by centuries of migration, war, and the relentless grind of survival. It is 2322, and the Sol system teeters on the brink of mutually assured destruction in a trilateral power struggle between the Inner Planets Concord (“the Forge”), the Helios Corporate League (“the Crucible”), and the Ouranos Ecumen Assembly (“the Garden”). These three giants hold each other in a deadly stalemate: the Forge’s overwhelming fleets, the Crucible’s He-3 monopoly, and the Garden’s irreplaceable food and biomedicine. 

You were the cogs of the corporate grind of the Crucible, fodder for the Forge, or glorified hostages of the Garden.  Each has their lofty goals and claims to be the guiding light for civilization but, in truth, all are riddled with corruption, lies, and naked ambition.
You are the mustered-out, the bought-out, the burned-out. A Forge marine who took the wrong side of a political purge. A Crucible executive whose performance bond was quietly cashed in. A Garden healer who asked one question too many. A Blue Choir navigator that heard a forbidden note in the blue.

Whatever path brought you here, your old career is over. Fate, politics, or simple bad luck cut it short before you could reach the top. You walked away with scars, secrets, and just enough credits to keep breathing.
Now you are Operators for the Crowned Republic of Ceres, a coalition of Belter and Void Clans of the Vaacci that heard the call of the Iron Mother, a prodigal captain and commadore deftly navigated the politics and fleet movements of the Helium Wars to avoid the Belt from being enslaved but also a gifted orator whose words swayed hearts and minds to the ideals of freedom and sovereignty.
You may not necessarily believe in the Iron other’s dream and the Crowned Republic does not demand it.  Do the job, make a profit, collect a fair share and the most elusive and often overlooked thing of value in the Sol system; to live free of the invisible leashes of gold, ideology, or servitude.

Loyalty is negotiable. Some of you are true Belters, void-born and proud, ready to die under the meteoric circlet. Others are temporary hires, counting the days until a better offer—or a way home—appears. A few are plants, feeding secrets back to old masters for promised pardon. Most are simply survivors who discovered that the Crown’s brand of freedom, however rough, beats the gilded cages of the great powers.
Every contract is a gamble. Succeed and you earn shares, reputation, maybe even a cutter of your own. Fail and you might still walk away—if the void is feeling generous.  For some, that may be a walk out of an airlock while for others it may be a walk of shame back to the gilded cages you had escaped.
